post_caption:
It's Masjid Khadijah! MasyaAllah! Of course, the hint was 'Ibu' because namanya Khadijah kan, wife of Rasulullah s.a.w and she is sometimes known as the mother of believers.

In 1915, a wealthy lady, Khadijah Binte Mohamed, created a wakaf and donated her asset to build a mosque. It was finally built in 1920, four years after the matron's passing. The architecture of the masjid was influenced by the Nagore Shrine in Ajmeere India and Masjid Nabawi in Madinah, that's why macam special gitu. In 2003,  a new Auditorium Building was opened by then Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong. 

Masjid Khadijah is now a resident msoque for Muslims living in the Geylang and Kallang area.

Did you know, at one point the mosque was even known as Masjid Bagarib, taking after the name of the imam of the mosque then. Today, besides serving the needs of residents and workers in the area, the mosque also houses the Religious Rehabilitation Group (RRG) which focuses on correcting the misinterpretation of Islamic concepts and dispel the extremist and terrorist ideologies that certain individuals have been indoctrinated with.

post_caption:
Masjid Darul Aman in Eunos!

Built in 1986 under the Mosque Building Fund (MBF) scheme, the mosque located at Jalan Eunos in the east can accommodate up to 3,500 people. Besides madrasah classes, it is also a popular venue for haj courses organised by travel agents. The mosque has since undergone a major addition and alteration project which was completed in 2005 and again in 2016.

Combining Malay architecture with Islamic art, the mosque is one of the few mosques in Singapore which features the pitched-roof structure commonly found in the Malay archipelago. The mosque replaces Masjid Aminah in Geylang which had to give way for redevelopment.

Did you know, Masjid Darul Aman was nominated for the prestigious Aga Khan Award in 1989 as an excellent example of tropical architecture?

post_caption:
Masjid Hajjah Fatimah! Indeed, this masjid is an icon and it was gazetted as a national monument on 28 June 1973.

Masjid Hajjah Fatimah is one of the few mosques named after a woman eh. The others being
Masjid Khadijah (Cik featured this last week) and Masjid Hajjah Rahimabi Kebun Limau.

Hajjah Fatimah was born in Melaka and was said to be married to a Bugis prince from the Celebes (Sulawesi). After his passing, Hajjah Fatimah, being the woman that she was, successfully carried on his trading business and amassed great wealth. 

Adik-adik tau tak that from historical accounts kan, her house was twice burgled and burned to the ground. Tapi Hajjah survived because she was away on both instances. Because of that, to demonstrate her gratitude to Allah s.w.t for having spared her life, she built a mosque on the land where her residence once stood. Begitulah backstory of the masjid. ðŸ˜Š

After her passing, Hajjah Fatimah was buried in a private enclosure behind the mosque, and was later joined by her daughter Raja Siti and her son-in-law Syed Ahmed bin Abdul-Rahman Alsagoff.

post_caption:
Masjid Jamek Queenstown!

The hint was 'some English princess' because this masjid is located at Margaret Drive, named after Princess Margaret Rose (adik kepada akak korang tu.. Queen Elizabeth II).

Masjid Jamek Queenstown was officially opened on 25 December 1964 to service a growing number of Muslims in the estate. The masjid was built from donations poured in by the community and residents living in the area and the masjid kan, has a very distinct minaret and Javanese architectural elements such as the tiered roof.

Adik-adik, did you know that in the 70s and 80s kan, Masjid Jamek Queenstown was easily flooded because it was located in a low lying area next to the Alexandra Canal. The stretch of road next to the Mosque was subsequently raised 6 times and the garden had to make way for a larger drainage system. Now you know! ðŸ˜ŠðŸ˜Š

post_caption:
You guessed it right! It is indeed Masjid Malabar!

It is hard to miss this mosque which sits at the junction of Victoria Street. The reason why Cik said the hint was 'Little Cousin' was because it is located very near to Masjid Sultan and it shares the unique golden dome(s), albeit smaller. ðŸ˜Š

Masjid Malabar serves the need of office workers in the area and is managed by the Malabar Muslim community, MasyaAllah. It wasn't the smoothest journey for the building of the mosque. At one point, there was a lack of funds to proceed with its completion. However, with Allah's grace, the funds eventually came in and it was completed. 

Masjid Malabar was declared opened on 24th January 1963 by the then Yang di-Pertuan Negara, Encik Yusof bin Ishak, the first President of Singapore.

post_caption:
Masjid Jamiyah Ar-Rabitah!

The mosque was officially opened in 1962 but plans to build the mosque started in the 1950s for the Muslim community in the area which used to be known as Alexandra City Council Quarters, Henderson Hill, and Redhill Road.

With the help of Jamiyah Singapore and the support from Haji Syed Ali Redha Alsagoff and Haji Baharuddin, a piece of land between Tiong Bahru Road and Henderson Road was obtained and approved by the Government for the site of a new mosque. Funds were then raised, including a huge donation from Jeddah-based charity, Rabitah Al-Alam Al-Islamiah. To commemorate the two organisations for the important role they played in the building of the mosque, the mosque was named â€œJamiyah Ar-Rabitahâ€.

In 1983, to better meet the growing needs of Muslims in the area, the mosque was demolished and rebuilt. It was officially reopened on 9 August 1985, in conjunction with the celebration of Singaporeâ€™s 20th National Day, by then Mufti of Singapore Syed Isa Semait.

While the mosque serves the religious needs of residents and office workers in the immediate area, did you know that Masjid Jamiyah Ar-Rabitah is also an important Social Development Mosque which serves and disburses Zakat to many needy Muslims resident in the area, many of whom are elderlies and those with special needs. â¤ï¸â¤ï¸

post_caption:
Masjid Jamae (Chulia)!

Ahh, this mosque is not difficult to find or notice eh... With dia punya mint green exterior and located in a Chinese heritage area, definitely very striking ye! Also, you would also realise that its neighbour nearby is Sri Mariaman Hindu temple. Two different places of worship side-by-side in a Chinatown - #UniquelySingapore.

Masjid Jamae Chulia is one of the oldest mosques in Singapore tau. It has been established since 1826, just seven years after the founding of modern Singapore! The Chulia Indian immigrants rebuilt the mosque between 1830 and 1835. Masjid Jamae was one of the three mosques built by these Indian Muslims who came to work mostly as traders and money changers. The other two mosques are Nagore Durgha (1828-1830) and Al-Abrar Mosque (1850-1855).

The masjid's architecture and design are unique. While the entrance gate is distinctively South Indian, the two prayer halls and the shrine are in the Neo-Classical style typical of George Drumgoole Coleman, the first trained architect in Singapore. This uniqueness of Jamae Mosque made it a well-photographed landmark that may be seen in postcards from the 19th century to the present day.

This Mosque was gazetted as a national monument on 19 November 1974, and is believed to be the oldest of the five mosques gazetted as national monuments in Singapore; Jamae Chulia mosque, Al-Abrar mosque, Sultan mosque, Abdul Gafoor Mosque and Hajjah Fathimah Mosque.

MasyaAllah! â¤ï¸ May our houses of worship and heritage be protected always, InsyaAllah. Amin.
